    <tr>
        <td width="549" colspan="4"><p>We implemented five different group key 
            agreement protocols using <a href="http://www.openssl.org">OpenSSL</a>. 
            All five protocols have similar structure.</p>
            <p><img src="images/banner26.gif" border="0" class="namo-bullet2"> 
            Each protocol requires communication facility such as group communication 
            system<br> <img src="images/banner26.gif" border="0" class="namo-bullet2"> 
            Each protocol requires OpenSSL. OpenSSL version should be at least 
            0.9.4.<br> <img src="images/banner26.gif" border="0" class="namo-bullet2"> 
            Installation information is provided as README file in each gzipped 
            tar file<br> <img src="images/banner26.gif" border="0" class="namo-bullet2"> 
            All APIs have been tested in Linux/x86 and Solaris/Sparc. However it should 
            run on other plataforms without heavy modifications (if any), as long as the
            other requirements (i.e. openssl) are met. &nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<ul>
<li><a href="download/clq_api1.0.tar.gz">clq_api-1.0 Download</a>
<li><a href="download/CLQ_LICENSE">LICENSE</a>
<li><a href="download/README">README</a>
<li><a href="download/README_certificates">README related with certificate handling</a>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li> STR
  <ul>
     <li>Based on <em>A Secure Audio Teleconference System</em> by
            D. Steer, L. Strawczynski, W. Diffie and M. Wiener  
            presented at Crypto'88
     <li>STR protocol is modified to provide dynamic group operation
     <li>Group Key Structure<br> <img src="download_html_eqn1.gif"
            NAMO_EQN__><!--NAMO_EQN__ 208 1
            K_{n}=g^{N_{n}g^{N_{n-1}\cdots g^{N_{2}N_{1}}}} -->&nbsp;
     <li>Advantage
       <ul>
       <li>Low communication overhead(two round for additive operation
         and one round for subtractive operation) 
       <li>Well-suited for adding new group members(two modular 
            exponentiation)
       <li>Robustness is easily provided(included in this package)
       </ul>
     <li>Disadvantage
       <ul>
       <li>Relatively difficult member exclusion(O(n) modular exp.)
       </ul>
  </ul>
  <li> BD
  <ul>
     <li>Based on <em>A Secure and Efficient Conference 
            Key Distribution System</em> by M. Burmester and Y. Desmedt presented 
            at EUROCRYPT '94
     <li>BD protocol is modified to provide dynamic group operation
     <li>Group Key Structure<br> <img src="download_html_eqn2.gif"
            NAMO_EQN__><!--NAMO_EQN__ 160 1
            K_{n}=g^{N_{1}N_{2}+N_{2}N_{3}+ \cdots
            +N_{n-1}N_{n}+N_{n}N_{1}} -->&nbsp;      
     <li>Advantage
       <ul>
       <li>Low computational overhead(two modular exponentiations)
       </ul>
     <li>Disadvantage
       <ul>
       <li>High communication cost(<i>2n</i> broadcast is required)
       <li>Whenever membership change happens, at least half of session 
            random needs to be refreshed.
       </ul>
  </ul>
  <li> GDH
  <ul>
     <li>Based on <a href="paper/stw99.pdf"><i>Key Agreement in
         Dynamic Peer Groups</i></a> by <a
         href="http://www.zurich.ibm.com/~sti/">M.  Steiner</a>, <a
         href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~gts">G. Tsudik</a> and <a
         href="http://www.zurich.ibm.com/~wmi/">M. Waidner</a>
         presented at IEEE Transaction on Parallel and Distributed
         Systems, Aug. 2000.   
     <li>Group Key Structure<br> <img src="download_html_eqn3.gif"
         NAMO_EQN__><!--NAMO_EQN__ 160 1 K_n=g^{N_1 N_2 \cdots N_n}
         -->&nbsp;
     <li>Advantage
       <ul>
       <li>High security assurance
       </ul>
     <li>Disadvantage
       <ul>
       <li>Relatively high computation cost(<i>O(n)</i> modular exponentiation)
       <li>Relatively hard to provide robustness
       </ul>
  </ul>
  <li> CKD
  <ul>
     <li>Centralized key distribution scheme providing same security
         guarantee as GDH
  </ul>
  <li> TGDH
  <ul>
     <li>Based on <a href="paper/kpt2000.pdf"><i>Simple 
            and Fault-Tolerant Key Agreement for Dynamic Collaborative Groups</i></a><i> 
            </i>by <a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~kyongdae">Y. Kim</a>, <a href="http://paris.cs.berkeley.edu/~perrig">A. 
            Perrig</a>, and <a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~gts">G. Tsudik</a> 
            presented at ACMCCS 2000.
     <li>Group Key Structure for 8 users<br> <img
         src="download_html_eqn4.gif" NAMO_EQN__><!--NAMO_EQN__ 208 1
         K_n = g^{g^{g^{N_1N_2}g^{N_3N_4}}g^{g^{N_5N_6}g^{N_7N_8}}} 
	 -->&nbsp;
     <li>Advantage
       <ul>
       <li>Low communication overhead(requires maximum 2 round 
            except multiple leave)
       <li>Low computation overhead(maximum <i>4 log n</i> modular 
            exponentiation)
       <li>Easy to provide robustness
       </ul>
     <li>Disadvantage
       <ul>Relatively high communication cost for multiple leave(<i>O(log n)</i>)
       </ul>
  </ul>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
